      "body": "**I'm submitting a ...**  (check one with \"x\")\r\n```\r\n[ ] bug report => search github for a similar issue or PR before submitting\r\n[x] feature request\r\n[ ] support request => Please do not submit support request here, instead see https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#question\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Current behavior**\r\nThere is no option to route root modules. And there can be only one.\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior**\r\nThere should be a option to route root modules. That would replace `<app />` content in index.html.\r\n\r\n**What is the motivation / use case for changing the behavior?**\r\nMost websites feature two start-points - / (public interface) and /admin (admin interface). Mostly those have totally different components, styles, etc., but services and data layers are common. \r\n\r\nAs so much stuff differs, it makes sense to Lazy load admin and public modules, that contain it's respective sub-routes (like /admin/accounts for admin or /news for public). But there we face some limitations. There can be only one root module! Lazy loaded child modules can't use \"bootstrap\" option, so can't have own root component with respective layout. \r\n\r\nFor now I see 2 possible solutions:\r\n\r\nA) Have totally different angular projects for admin and public,\r\nB) Create admin.html and index.html in root /src - those would have own different root modules.\r\n\r\nA) is bad because, again, lot's of code still can be common.\r\nB) You have to input URL, like localhost:3000/admin.html, or configure web server and that all will fail if URL translations are necessary for the project :(\r\n\r\n**Please tell us about your environment:**\r\nWindows 10, Atom, WebPack\r\n* **Angular version:** 2.0.0\r\n* **Browser:** Chrome latest, stable\r\n* **Language:** all\r\n"
